1 Introduction

In this project, we focus on analyzing motorsport telemetry data, using data from the 2018 to 2024 Formula 1 (F1) seasons. Formula 1 has a huge amount of data used widely in the sport, making it perfect for visualization and analysis. This project centers on the analysis of F1 qualifying sessions, highlighting comparisons between two drivers in the same race or the same driver across different seasons. We built a Shiny application to allow users to interactively explore qualifying data and create custom visualizations by selecting drivers, seasons, and circuits. As case studies, we look at different qualifying sessions, both across years with the same driver, and across drivers during the same race. For looking at different years, we will look at the SÃ£o Paulo Grand Prix in 2023 versus in 2024. For comparing drivers, we will look at Charles Leclerc and Oscar Piastri during the 2024 Monaco Grand Prix.

1.1 Outline

We begin by exploring what Formula 1 is and how a race weekend is scheduled in SectionÂ 1.2. We then look at why specifically qualifying sessions are important for a weekend, why theyâre ideal for analysis, and what we hope to explore in the data in SectionÂ 1.3. In SectionÂ 2.1, we look at the R package f1dataR , to explore its general usage, as well as why it was instrumental to this project. We go into some more detail about the data used for the plots of the app in ?@sec-data. Then, in SectionÂ 2.3, we look at how the shiny app was developed, and how a user might utilize it explore a quaifying session. We then look at two case studies in SectionÂ 3.1 and SectionÂ 3.2 for two examples of how the functions can be used to visualize data, and highlight how contrasting elements like weather or track layout make for interesting qualifying sessions. We also look at a case study in SectionÂ 3.3 to observe the variation between teammates, because they typically have the same machinery We end with SectionÂ 4 to talk about what future work could be done to make the Shiny app more robust, as well as SectionÂ 5, which highlights relevant functions and code used to create the Shiny app.

1.2 What is Formula 1?

Formula 1 (F1) is an international motorsport series governed by the FÃ©dÃ©ration Internationale de lâAutomobile (FIA), involving 20 drivers across 10 âconstructorsâ that compete in 18-24 race weekends across a season. A âconstructorâ is essentially a team, which develops a car for the season, and has two drivers that drive for them. he group of drivers/teams for a season is commonly referred to as the âgrid,â named for the grid-like shap that drivers line up in prior to a race start. One is the World Constructorâs Championship (WCC), given to the team with the most points across both drivers.

The combination of drivers and teams mean there are two different goals come at the end of an F1 season. The other is the World Driverâs Championship (WDC), given to the individual driver with the most points. Though completely separate, it is very uncommon for the driver that wins the World Championship to be from a different team than that who wins the WCC. Since 2000, there have only been three seasons where the team that won the WCC, did not also produce the WDC.

A âtypicalâ race weekend of the F1 season features practice, qualifying, and race sessions, each serving a different purpose. All race weekends tend to be Friday through Sunday, keeping the same schedule in order to remain as consistent as possible. Fridays involve two âfree practiceâ sessions where they can change car setups at will to allow for the teams to gather data to prepare for the race. The first session, Free Practice 1 (FP1) is 60 minutes long, and will typically be focused on getting used to the track and any changes that may have been made from previous seasons, test setups, and gathering data. The second session, aptly named Free Practice 2 (FP2), is also 60 minutes long, but will typically involve longer race simulations and tire degradation. Saturdays also have two sessions scheduled, one final Free Practice 3 (FP3), and qualifying. FP3 is the final chance for setup changes and adjustments, and typically used for short qualifying-style runs. Qualifying is a knockout style session that sets the starting order for the race day on Sunday.

Because this project focuses on qualifying, weâll go into more detail about what that session actually looks like. Qualifying, sometimes shortened to âquali,â is split into three sessions, Q1, Q2, and Q3. Drivers are allowed to complete as many laps within the section as possible, with their fastest lap being counted towards the final standings in the session. Q1 is the longest session, at 18 minutes, and all 20 drivers compete but the slowest 5 are eliminated. Q2 is 15 minutes where the remaining 15 drivers compete and another 5 eliminated. The top 10 who make it to Q3 will use the session to finalize the order. It is important to note that positions are set at the end of the section, not at the end of the qualifying session, meaning that the bottom 5 eliminated will always make up starting places 20th-16th. This means that even if a car in Q2 goes a slower time than that of 16th, they will still qualify either 15th or above. It is possible then for a driver to have a faster lap than someone who qualified above them, but its rare.

The other important part of Formula 1 to mention is the tire compounds. F1âs sole tire sponsore is Pirelli, who supplies all the tires for the grid. The tires come in different compounds (soft, medium, hard) and are used for various track conditions and race strategies. The âslickâ dry tires are color-coded: red for soft, yellow for medium, and white for hard. There are two âwetâ tires for use when itâs raining, intermediate tires are green for damp conditions, and full wet tires are blue. For a race weekend, teams are provided with a certain number of sets for each driver, and must use at least two compounds during a race. Qualifying laps are almost always run on the soft tire, with the fastest laps typically coming in when drivers use a new soft, as it has the most grip but wears out quickly. Occasionally, you will see drivers on a used set of tires in qualifying to save a set for the race, or on a set of mediums if strategy might lead to using more softs later. 2018 is the only year in this project that utilized the âhypersoft,â âultrasoft,â and âsupersoftâ tires, which are now just all âsoft.â

This information is accurate through the end of the 2025 season, prior to F1 adding an eleventh team, Cadillac, and subsequently two more drivers to the grid.

1.3 Why Qualifying Laps?

A driverâs fastest lap from a qualifying session highlights driver skill, car setup efficiency, and team strategy under peak performance conditions, which provides a baseline to compare with. Unlike race laps, which are influenced by tire wear, fuel load, traffic, and strategy, qualifying laps are run under optimal conditions every time, because every thousandth of a second counts towards a better grid spot.

We say âoptimal conditionsâ to highlight the idea that any variations in speed are due to driver skill or superior car development, rather than unlucky strategy or tire wear. During qualifying, every driver is completing laps on low fuel and fresh (or almost fresh) tires, making them the fastest possible. Reducing the variability also allows for more direct comparisons when changing one variable, like the driver or season, while keeping everything else constant because they are always attempting a single flying lap under similar conditions. Additionally, because the focus is single flying laps, there are typically no interfering factors that vary lap time, like safety cars, overtaking, or pit stops. An important rule during qualifying is that cars on a âslow lapâ must move off the optimal racing line and out of the way of cars on flying laps, in order to reduce interference. The only interference that might occur during a lap is driver error, mechanical failure, or a safety hazard caused by the environment that would require reduced speed or aborting the lap.

Qualifying also holds a lot of strategic importance to the race weekend depending on the track. While there are some tracks where qualifying matters less to the race, like Max Verstappenâs incredible 17th to 1st drive at the 2024 SÃ£o Paulo Grand Prix, there many examples of where it determined the winner. We will look at a case study later that takes place in Monaco, which is a track infamous for its lack of overtaking opportunities, making qualifying all the more important.

2 Methods

2.1 The f1dataR Package

The f1dataR package is an R interface to access Formula 1 data, developed to make use of statistical tools in R with detailed motorsport telemetry and timing information. f1dataR leverages both the Jolpica API (formerly known as Ergast) for historical and session metadata, and a wrapper around the FastF1 Python library to extract rich telemetry data directly from F1âs live timing systems. Some examples of data that can be accessed through f1dataR specifically are session-level data and driver/constructor results. Session-level data includes information on race weekend structure (practice, qualifying, sprint, and race), including start times, session types, and circuit metadata, while results data includes, finishing positions, grid penalties, retirements, and historical performance going back to the inaugural F1 World Championship in 1950. In addition to this already robust dataset, f1dataR allows users to pull detailed telemetry data from every timed lap from 2018 through 2025, which includes speed traces, throttle and brake application, gear selection, DRS activation and car position (X, Y coordinates).

The package also includes some pre-made functions to make life easier for users. theme_track() modifies a ggplot object to look more like a track rather than a plot, and changes the colors to match Formula 1âs official color scheme. plot_fastest_lap() is used to simplify race data visualization and allow users to look at interesting data around gear or speed changes around a lap without needing to do any data manipulation themeselves.

In this project, we used f1dataR to load the fastest qualifying laps for specific drivers, seasons, and races, as well as access the telemetry data to analyze speed and gear changes, as well as visualize car positioning on the track using X/Y coordinates.

2.3 Shiny App

To make our analysis interactive and accessible, we developed a Shiny web application. The app can be found at https://stlawu.shinyapps.io/f1-qualifying-app/. This app has two main modes: one that allows users to compare two drivers in the same qualifying session, and one that compares how a single driver performed in different seasons at the same circuit. When first opening the app, there are three main tabs. The first has instructions for a user detailing the different comparison modes, as well as the two separate pages that actually have to do with the data we pulled.

For ease of explanation, all of the following examples will assume the user selected the âSame Sessionâ option to compare two drivers across a section.

The first page allows users to explore a variety of combinations of results through the âData Exploration Page.â First, the user will be able to select a year between 2018 and 2024. The app will then pull the race calendar from that season, and populate the race selection with the race names from that season. After selecting a race, the app will get all of the drivers that participated in the race, preventing issues later on with data not existing if a driver didnât compete for some reason, or if there had been a mid-season driver change in races prior. After selecting the four inputs, the app with show a table of all the lap times across drivers, a table with the driversâ final qualifying and race position, as well as a lollipop plot highlighting the tire usage across the session. In the lollipop plot there is typically a group of laps under a certain threshold, with another group tending to be between 12-20 seconds slower. Those laps are typically aborted laps, or âoutlaps,â and arenât necessarily used in the analysis, but are still useful to see.

The selection process for a single driver is similar, but you would first select the driver, then two seasons that they competed in, and then a race that existed in both seasons and had the driver compete in both. The app will then show the same three tables as before, but with the data from both seasons combined.

The second page allows users to either carry over their selections from the exploration, or pick new inputs to animate a qualifying lap comparison. The animation runs on a constant loop, meaning that it takes as long as the slowest lap time being compared, then starts over. The only additional input users can select is the âSmoothing Factor.â The smoothing factor affects the caption of the animation, which shows the current time, as well as the speed of each respective car at that fraction of a second. Because F1, especially qualifying is measured in thousandths of seconds, the telemetry data can have between 10 and 20 rows of data (speed, position, etc.) for a single second, making it difficult to read if the speed was left in its raw state. The smoothing factor takes the average speed over that number of frames, and uses that as the caption instead. We see a trade off, with higher factors making the plot more readable, but less accurate than a smaller factor.

3 Case Studies

3.1 2023 vs 2024 SÃ£o Paulo Grand Prix

The first case study will be comparing laps from the 2023 and 2024 SÃ£o Paulo Grand Prix. These two qualifying sessions highight the difference between wet weather and dry weather driving conditions, which might create the largest differential in lap times. This season comparison highlights how wet weather conditions in 2023 led to significantly slower lap times compared to the dry conditions in 2024, as the on track positions for Lando Norris between the two seasons are drastically far from each other.

It is important to note that from year to year, there is some variance in lap times that already exists due to car and driver development, but keeping the driver (and constructor) the same seeks to mitigate some of the variance. We will see more examples later in this section about how qualifying lap times vary between teammates, as well as constructors.

3.2 2024 Monaco Grand Prix

Monaco is likely the most famous Formula 1 race that still exists on the calendar today, especially as many of its historic counterparts have been removed due to safety concerns based on how old the tracks are. Since it was added to the calendar, the track layout through the streets of Monte Carlo has essentially remained unchanged, and is the only track that sits below the FIAâs minimum length due to its history (and the inability to make it any longer). What has changed since 1950 when the race started being on the calendar annually is the size of Formula 1 cars. Alongside its history Monaco is not infamous for being one of the least interesting F1 races because it is almost impossible for cars to overtake each other on track. This means though, that a driverâs Saturday qualifying result, is even more important, as the phrase âMonaco is won on Saturdayâ holds true in most seasons.

This case study compares Oscar Piastri and Charles Leclercâs fastest qualifying laps from 2024. The two drivers, from different constructors, both nearing the front of the constructors championship, can show how important it is to find every last thousandth of pace in a lap.

With a first lap crash and safety car allowing drivers to change tires immediately without fear of losing on strategy to another team, the 2024 Monaco Grand Prix essentially consisted of every driver going around in circles for the duration of the race, with the finishing order being almost identical to the starting order (bar a few DNFs). While not so interesting to watch live, it highlights how important qualifying is to a driverâs success.

3.3 2024 Canadian Grand Prix

For the next case study, we are going to observe two drivers from the reigning Constructorsâ Champions. To provide some context, Max Verstappen, Sergio PÃ©rez, and Red Bull are coming off one of the most dominant seasons in F1 history, with Verstappen winning the WDC by 290 points (575 points to teammate PÃ©rezâs 285 in second) and Red Bull winning the WCC by over 400. If you took away all of PÃ©rezâs points from Red Bull, they still wouldâve won by 166 points. After that, everyone went into the 2024 season exepecting the exact same thing. Unfortunatey for Red Bull, and fortunately for anyone who likes to watch more than one team win, Red Bull did not dominate the 2024 season, and thatâs partially because of the gap in teammate performance. In the same car, Max Verstappen and Sergio PÃ©rez are qualifying on opposite ends of the grip.

The 2024 Canadian Grand Prix is one such example where in equal machinery, Verstappen is able to consistently extract more pace from the car than his teammate. While Max was fighting for pole position in Q3, PÃ©rez was eliminated in Q1. This case study highlights how even with the same car, the pace differential can be huge depending on the ability of the driver.

4 Conclusion

This project highlights how qualifying laps provide an interesting platform to experiment with performance analysis in F1. Looking at the influence of weather, to the verying importance of qualifying depending on track features, and differentials in driver performance are only some of the many case studies possible to look at.

Future work would include allowing users to customize what lap number they would like to animate, as there are interesting things to be analyzed from laps that are not the drivers fastest lap. For one, if there were rain at the end of a session in Q3, we are unable at the moment to actually visualize what the pole lap would look like, because it will likely not be the fastest. There are also the rare instances we mentioned earlier, where hazards like a red or yellow flag force a driver to slow on a flying lap. In this case, it would be ideal to observe how close the pace was up until the flags came out.

Another feature to add would be the ability to pause, play, and speed up or slow down the animation depending on what users are trying to observe from the plot. If someone were interested in just one corner, its not efficent nor pleasant to stare at the circles just to catch the millisecond theyâre at the apex.

Data plays a crucial role in Formula 1, and visual analytics can offer fans a deeper understanding of qualifying performance. Interactive tools like Shiny help make F1 data more accessible, insightful, and enjoyable for the average viewer.

server <- function(input, output, session) {
  #### Functions ####

  # fetch qualifying data
  fetch_quali_data <- function(season, round) {
    tryCatch(
      {
        results <- load_session_laps(season, round, "Q")
        if (is.null(results) || nrow(results) == 0) return(NULL)
        results
      },
      error = function(e) NULL
    )
  }

  fetch_quali_data_seasons <- function(season_a, season_b, round) {
    tryCatch(
      {
        results_a <- load_session_laps(season_a, round, "Q") |> mutate(season = season_a)
        results_b <- load_session_laps(season_b, round, "Q") |> mutate(season = season_b)
        if (is.null(results_a) || is.null(results_b) || nrow(results_a) == 0 || nrow(results_b) == 0) {
          return(NULL)
        } else {
          results <- bind_rows(results_a, results_b)
          return(results)
        }

      },
      error = function(e) NULL
    )
  }

    full_results_b <- load_results(input$season_b, round_num_b) |> mutate(season = input$season_b)

    full_results <- bind_rows(full_results_a, full_results_b)

    driver_data <- load_drivers(input$season_a)

      driver2_data <- get_quali_telemetry(laps = "fastest", season = input$season_1, round = input$round_1, driver = input$driver_2, verbose = TRUE)

      # smooth the track data
      track_data(smooth_track(driver1_data))

      # assign driver labels
      driver1_data <- driver1_data |> mutate(driver = input$driver_1)
      driver2_data <- driver2_data |> mutate(driver = input$driver_2)

      # combine telemetry data
      combined_data <- bind_data_driver(driver1_data, driver2_data, drivers = c(input$driver_1, input$driver_2))

      # smooth speed values

      smooth_speed(plot_data = combined_data, grouping = "driver", input$smoothing_factor)

      # only proceed if animation is still running
      if (animation_running()) {
        plot_data(combined_data)
      }
    } else {
      animation_running(TRUE)

      # fetch telemetry data
      req(input$driver_same, input$season_a, input$season_b, input$round_constant)

      driver_seasona_data <- get_quali_telemetry(laps = "fastest", season = input$season_a, round = input$round_constant, driver = input$driver_1, verbose = TRUE)
      driver_seasonb_data <- get_quali_telemetry(laps = "fastest", season = input$season_b, round = input$round_constant, driver = input$driver_1, verbose = TRUE)

      # smooth the track data
      track_data(smooth_track(driver_seasona_data))

      # assign season labels

      driver_seasonb_data <- driver_seasonb_data |> mutate(season = input$season_b)

      # combine telemetry data
      combined_data <- bind_rows(driver_seasona_data, driver_seasonb_data) |> mutate(season = as.factor(season))

      smooth_speed(plot_data = combined_data, grouping = "season", input$smoothing_factor)

      # only proceed if animation is still running
      if (animation_running()) {
        plot_data(combined_data)
      }
    }

  driver_colors <- reactive({

        labs(

      animation <- animate(animated_plot, width = 700, height = 700, fps = 10, renderer = gifski_renderer())

      req(plot_data(), track_data(), animation_running())  # Ensure animation is running

      t_df <- track_data()
      plot_data <- plot_data()

      start_coord <- t_df |> slice(1)

      season_colors <- season_colors()

      static_plot <- ggplot() +
        geom_path(data = t_df, aes(x = x2, y = y2, group = 1),
                  linewidth = 8, color = "white") +
        geom_point(data = start_coord, aes(x = x2, y = y2),
                   color = "black", shape = 18, size = 4) +
        geom_point(data = plot_data(), aes(x = x, y = y, group = season, color = season),
                   size = 3) +
        scale_color_manual(values = season_colors) +
        theme_track() +
        theme(plot.title = element_text(family = "titillium", face = "bold", size = 20, color = "#aa1a0a"),
              plot.subtitle = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16, color = "white"),
              plot.caption = element_text(face = "plain", size = 16, color = "white")) +
        labs(title = paste(input$season_a, "vs.", input$season_b, "Qualifying Lap"),
             subtitle = paste(input$driver_same, input$round_constant),
             x = NULL, y = NULL)

      # apply track correction
      corrected_plot <- corrected_track(static_plot, plot_data())

      animated_plot <- corrected_plot +
        transition_reveal(along = time) +
        ease_aes('linear') +
        labs(
          caption = paste(
            "Time: {sprintf('%.3f', frame_along)} s\n",
            input$season_a, " Speed: {plot_data$speed_smooth[which.min(abs(plot_data$time[plot_data$season == input$season_a] - frame_along))]} kph\n",
            input$season_b," Speed: {plot_data$speed_smooth[which.min(abs(plot_data$time[plot_data$season == input$season_b] - frame_along))]} kph"
          )
        )

      outfile <- tempfile(fileext = ".gif")
      animation <- animate(animated_plot, width = 700, height = 700, fps = 10, renderer = gifski_renderer())
      anim_save(outfile, animation = animation)
    }
    hideSpinner()

    # return a list containing the filename
    list(src = outfile, contentType = 'image/gif')

  }, deleteFile = TRUE)
}

shinyApp(ui, server)
